1. Source Documents (Evidence of Transactions)
These are the primary papers that record business transactions:
Invoices (Sales Invoices) – proof of sales to customers
Purchase Invoices – proof of purchases from suppliers
Receipts – cash received evidence
Payment Vouchers – proof of payments made
Bank Statements – record of cash and bank transactions
Cheque Copies – payments via bank
Credit Notes / Debit Notes – adjustments to invoices
Expense Bills – for expenses like utilities, rent, salaries
Petty Cash Vouchers – small day-to-day cash expenses

2.Daybook/Journals (Books of Original Entry)
Cash Book – records all cash and bank transactions
Sales Journal – records all credit sales
Purchase Journal – records all credit purchases
General Journal – records non-cash or adjusting transactions
Petty Cash Book – small cash transactions

3. Ledgers
General Ledger – summary of all accounts (assets, liabilities, equity, income, expenses)
Subsidiary Ledgers
Accounts Receivable Ledger (customers)
Accounts Payable Ledger (suppliers)
Inventory Ledger

4. Trial Balance & Adjusting Papers
Trial Balance – summarizes ledger balances to check accounting equality
Adjusting Entries Papers – accruals, deferrals, provisions, depreciation

5. Financial Statements / Reports
Balance Sheet (Statement of Financial Position) – assets, liabilities, equity
Income Statement (Profit & Loss Account) – revenues, expenses, profit/loss
Cash Flow Statement – cash inflows and outflows
Statement of Changes in Equity – equity movements
Notes to Accounts – explanations and disclosures

6. Regulatory & Compliance Papers
Tax Returns & Forms (VAT, Income Tax, etc.)
Audit Reports – internal or external
Bank Reconciliation Statements
Internal Control Checklists

7. Specialized Accounting Papers
Inventory Records / Stock Sheets
Payroll Registers
Depreciation Schedules
Accounts Receivable Aging Report
Accounts Payable Aging Report
💡 Tip: For companies following IFRS or GAAP, additional supporting papers like provision schedules, impairment analysis, and segment reporting papers may also be required.
